    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_267967263" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/267967263" />
    <a title="K. Lincoln" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2664606-k-lincoln"><img alt="K. Lincoln" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1540477668p2/2664606.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/267967263?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K. Lincoln" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K. Lincoln" href="/user/show/2664606-k-lincoln">K. Lincoln</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer267967263" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15030745180396132870">I came back to the Sebastian St. Cyr series after a year&apos;s time and found that I love it now just as much as I did when I first cracked open the pages of What Angels Fear (which I had started because I was going through Deanna Raybourn withdrawal.)<br/><br/>The third book in this series of Viscount St. Cyr&apos;s unorthodox investigation into murders that touch the nobility continues the delicious exploration of Sebastian&apos;s character amidst the themes of honor, self-sacrifice, and trust.<br/><br/>A killer is following t</span>
  <span id="freeText15030745180396132870" style="display:none">I came back to the Sebastian St. Cyr series after a year's time and found that I love it now just as much as I did when I first cracked open the pages of What Angels Fear (which I had started because I was going through Deanna Raybourn withdrawal.)<br /><br />The third book in this series of Viscount St. Cyr's unorthodox investigation into murders that touch the nobility continues the delicious exploration of Sebastian's character amidst the themes of honor, self-sacrifice, and trust.<br /><br />A killer is following the lines of a John Donne poem, arranging the young, male victims purposefully to echo the poem. Sebastian and his usual compatriots, Gibson the anatomologist and doctor and Sir Henry the magistrate, look into the strange deaths only to find the mystery's threads leading to his own father, the Earl of Hendon.<br /><br />I don't read St. Cyr mysteries to unravel a logical puzzle, rather, one follows Sebastian in his meandering investigations in order to experience with him the constant testing of his resolve to do what is right in the face of society's blacker desires and lies.<br /><br />You know, as in the other books, there will be angsty love between him and his mistress, Kat, and you know he will butt heads with Lord Jarvis, and you know he will be beaten by ruffians, and in the end, his father will wound Sebastian's tender heart with a twisted revelation, but knowing these things in advance doesn't lessen the pleasure.<br /><br />What is so compelling for me in these books is how Sebastian, with his military past, ability to callously beat and kill ruffians, and the selfish evil he's seen in the course of his investigations, still cannot resist investigating, even when his heart truly wants to trust and love those around him; even when those closest to him (his father, his sister, Kat) are all keeping secrets from him. He can't resist his own fierce desire to love.<br /><br />The mystery, the poem, Sebastian's relationships, and his past, all combine in a historical mystery that leaves you slightly more emotionally raw then when you first started the book.<br /><br />This Book's Snack Rating: Black bean tortilla chips and habanero salsa, so satisfying on many levels to eat, and despite the growing sting of the habanero on the tongue you can't quite resist eating chip after chip.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15030745180396132870" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


