<div id="review_2361650056" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2361650056" />
    <a title="Andree" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2863963-andree"><img alt="Andree" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2361650056?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andree" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andree" href="/user/show/2863963-andree">Andree</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781101212011" href="/book/show/9093763-why-mermaids-sing">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2863963-andree?shelf=2018">2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2361650056" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4256406711536621844">2020 reread<br/><br/>This was also better on reread. I&apos;d bump up to 3.5 stars, I think. The Kat continues to be better when you know where it&apos;s going. So even though this one was repetitive, it&apos;s less annoying. Also, the Kat-as-spy plotline took up less space than I remembered. Plus, the actual mystery is fairly solid, if a little disturbing (another reason I&apos;m not bumping up to 4 stars).<br/><br/> I wasn&apos;t looking to the reread of book 4, because as I recall, Sebastian angsts all over the place for most of the boo</span>
  <span id="freeText4256406711536621844" style="display:none">2020 reread<br /><br />This was also better on reread. I'd bump up to 3.5 stars, I think. The Kat continues to be better when you know where it's going. So even though this one was repetitive, it's less annoying. Also, the Kat-as-spy plotline took up less space than I remembered. Plus, the actual mystery is fairly solid, if a little disturbing (another reason I'm not bumping up to 4 stars).<br /><br /> I wasn't looking to the reread of book 4, because as I recall, Sebastian angsts all over the place for most of the book, but then I remembered that when he isn't angsting all over the place, he's hanging out with Hero, so I am cautiously optimistic.<br /><br />Anyway, I like how the relationships are done in this. Sebastian's relationship with Hendon is still one of my favourites.<br /><br />2018<br /><br />Default 3 star rating. It's probably better than that (at least half a star, if not a full one), but I'm not rating it higher, because I don't feel like it. <br /><br />The mystery aspects are quite good. I continue to enjoy Lovejoy. Hero Jarvis providing a key piece of information was fun. A lot of the character stuff is good. Sebastian's relationships with Tom, with his doctor friend, and with his father are all interesting and well developed. Totally there for that.<br /><br />The Kat stuff though, it's problematic. For the first half of the book it's boring, and then, yeah. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I mean, I'm totally done with the Kat as spy plotline. I was done at least one book ago. Glad the books seem to be to (I hope). And their relationship was always tedious, and never went anywhere. But her turning out to be his half-sister seems... extreme. I mean, it wasn't even necessary to prevent the marriage (I do like her scheme for not marrying him, before their relationship is discovered). It's just so dramatic, and odd. I assume it's going somewhere with the weird family tensions in the St. Cyr family, BUT STILL. Anytime my reaction to a 'plot twist' is to say <i>"Seriously??"</i> out loud, fairly certain it's not ideal. I suppose I should count my blessings - at least it means the relationship itself is theoretically done. Just not looking forward to what I assume will be a whole boatload of Kat-related angst in Book 4. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="4256406711536621844" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


